<div class='layout'><p>Hari Seldon……back in……chair in……alcove that……been assigned to……through Dors Venabilis intervention. He……dissatisfied. </p><p>待在由铎丝·凡纳比里帮他在图书馆争取到的一间凹室中，哈里·谢顿靠在一张椅子上，心里感到很不满意。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>As a matter of fact, although that……the expression he used in……mind, he knew that it……a gross underestimation of……feelings. He……not simply dissatisfied, he……furious--all……more so because he wasnt sure what it……he……furious about.……it about……histories?……writers……compilers of histories?……worlds……people that made……histories? </p><p>事实上，虽然那正是他心中使用的词汇，他也知道“不满意”实在太过低估如今的感觉。他不只不满意，简直就是愤怒。而他又不确定到底为何愤怒，更是为这股怒焰火上加油。他是在气历史吗？还是气那些史书的作者与编者？或是创造历史的各个世界与全体人类？</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Whatever……target of……fury, it didnt really matter. What counted……that……notes were useless,……new knowledge……useless, everything……useless. </p><p>不论他发怒的对象为何，其实都没什么关系。重要的是他做的笔记没有用，他学到的新知识没有用，一切的一切都没有用。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He……been at……University……for almost……weeks. He……managed to find a computer outlet at……very start……with it……begun work--without instruction,……using……instincts he……developed over a number of years of mathematical labors. It……been slow……halting,……there……a certain pleasure in gradually determining……routes by which he could……his questions answered.</p><p>如今，他来到这所大学已将近六周。一开始他就设法找到一套电脑终端机，利用它展开工作……没有任何人指导，仅靠自己钻研数学多年所累积的直觉。进度虽然缓慢，而且并不顺利，不过渐渐发现走哪条路便能找到问题的答案，也自有一番乐趣。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Then came……week of instruction with Dors, which……taught……several dozen shortcuts……had brought with it……sets of embarrassments.……first……included……sidelong glances he received from……undergraduates,……seemed contemptuously aware of……greater……and……were disposed to frown a……at Dorss constant……of……honorific "Doctor" in addressing him. </p><p>后来，铎丝教授的一周课程开始了。这门课教给他数十种捷径，却也带来两组尴尬的窘境。其一包括那些大学生斜眼看人，似乎因为察觉到他的年龄而瞧不起他；每当铎丝频频使用“博士”的尊衔称呼他，他们全都会稍微皱皱眉头。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>I don't want them to think,……said, "that youre some backward perpetual student taking remedial history."</p><p>“我不希望他们认为，”她说，“你是个永远毕不了业的老学生，正在补修历史学分。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But surely youve established……point. Surely, a mere Seldon is sufficient now."</p><p>“但你显然已经表明这一点。现在只要叫我‘谢顿’当然就够了。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"No," Dors said……smiled suddenly. "Besides, I like to call……Dr. Seldon. I like……way……look uncomfortable each time."</p><p>“不行。”铎丝突然微微一笑，“此外，我喜欢叫你‘谢顿博士’，我喜欢看你每次露出那种不自在的表情。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"You have a peculiar sense of sadistic humor."</p><p>“你有一种虐待狂的幽默感。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Would……deprive me?"</p><p>“你要剥夺我的乐趣吗？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>For some reason, that made……laugh. Surely,……natural reaction would have been to deny sadism. Somehow he found it pleasant that……accepted……ball of conversation……fired it back.……thought……to a natural question.……you play tennis here at……University?"</p><p>不知道为什么，这句话令他开怀大笑。不用说，自然的反应当然应该是否认自己有虐待狂倾向。没想到她却接下这一记“杀球”，并立即予以反击，他觉得实在好玩。这个想法自然而然引发了一个问题：“你在学校打不打网球？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"We have courts,……I don't play."</p><p>“我们有网球场，但是我不会打。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Good.……teach you.……when I……Ill call……Professor Venabili."</p><p>“很好，我来教你。而我在球场上，会称呼你凡纳比里教授。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Thats what……call me in class anyway."</p><p>“反正你在课堂上就是这样称呼我的。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Youll be surprised……ridiculous it will sound on……tennis court."</p><p>“你不会相信它在网球场上听起来多么滑稽。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I……get to like it."</p><p>“我可能会喜欢。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"In that case, I will……to find what else……might……to like."</p><p>“这样的话，我会试图找出你还可能喜欢些什么。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I……you have a peculiar sense of salacious humor."</p><p>“我发现你有一种色情狂的幽默感。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>She……put that ball in that spot deliberately……he said, "Would……deprive me?"</p><p>她故意把这记杀球打到同一个地方，于是他说：“你要剥夺我的乐趣吗？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>She smiled……later……surprisingly well on……tennis court.</p><p>她微笑不语。后来，她在网球场上表现得出奇优异。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Are……sure……never played tennis?" he said, puffing, after……session.</p><p>“你确定自己从没打过网球？”打完一局后，他喘着气问道。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Positive,"……said.</p><p>“确定。”她说。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The other……of embarrassments……more private. He learned……necessary techniques of historical research……then burned--in private--at……earlier attempts to make……of……computers memory. It……simply an entirely different mind-set from that used in mathematics. It……equally logical, he supposed, since it could be used, consistently……without error, to move in whatever direction he wanted……but it……a substantially different brand of logic from that to which he……accustomed.</p><p>另一组窘境比较属于私人性质。当他学会查询历史资料的必要技巧，开始试图使用电脑记忆组的时候，曾经（私底下）一败涂地。那简直是与数学界全然不同的思考模式。他认为它应该同样合乎逻辑，因为它可以毫无矛盾、毫无错误地根据他的心意四通八达，可是这种逻辑与他熟悉的那套完全不同。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>But with or without instructions, whether he stumbled or moved in swiftly, he simply didnt……any results.</p><p>但不论有没有人指导，不论是跌跌撞撞或迅速进入情况，他就是不能得到任何结果。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>His annoyance made itself felt on……tennis court. Dors quickly reached……stage where it……no longer necessary to……easy balls at……to give……time to judge direction……distance. That made it easy to forget that……was just a beginner……he expressed……anger in……swing, firing……ball back at……as though it were a laser beam made solid.</p><p>他的恼怒在网球场上露出痕迹。铎丝很快就有长足的进步，他不必再为了给她时间来判断方向与距离，而喂给她好打的高吊球。这使他很容易忘掉她只是个初学者，不知不觉便将愤怒发泄在挥拍动作上，将球使劲向她击去，仿佛射出一道化作固体的激光光束。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>She came trotting up to……net……said, "I……understand your wanting to kill……since it must annoy……to watch me miss……shots so often.……is……though, that……managed to miss my head by about three centimeters that time? I mean,……didnt even nick……Cant……do better than that?"</p><p>她小跑步来到网前。“我能了解你为什么想要杀我，因为看到我频频漏接，一定让你非常恼火。可是，为什么要让球偏离我的脑袋三厘米左右呢？我的意思是，你甚至没打中我的汗毛，你能不能瞄得更准一点？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon, horrified, tried to explain,……only managed to sound incoherent.</p><p>谢顿吓呆了，连忙想要解释，却只说出一串语无伦次的话。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>She said, "Look. Im……going to face……other returns of yours today, so……don't we shower……then……together……some……and whatever……you……tell me just what……were trying to kill. If it wasnt my poor head……if……don't……the real victim……your chest, youll be entirely……dangerous on……other side of……net……me to want to serve as a target."</p><p>她说：“听着，今天我不想再接你的球了。所以我们何不这就去淋浴，再一起喝杯茶什么的，然后你可以告诉我，你想要杀的究竟是什么。如果不是我这颗可怜的脑袋，又如果你不将元凶从心头拔除，那么让你站在球网另一边，把我当成你的靶子，对我而言实在太危险了。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Over……he said, "Dors,……scanned history after history; just scanned, browsed. I haven't……time……deep study yet. Even……its become obvious.……the book-films concentrate on……same……events."</p><p>喝茶的时候，他说：“铎丝，我已经扫描过无数的历史，只是扫描和浏览而已，我还没有时间做深入研究。即使如此，有件事已经十分明显，所有的影视书都只探讨相同的少数事件。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Crucial ones. History-making ones."</p><p>“关键的事件，创造历史的事件。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Thats just an excuse. Theyre copying each other. There……twenty-five million worlds……there……theres significant mention of perhaps twenty-five."</p><p>“那只是个借口，其实它们相互抄袭。银河系共有两千五百万个世界，记载详细的也许只有二十五个。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Dors said, "Youre reading general Galactic histories only. Look up……special histories of some of……minor worlds. On every world, however small,……children……taught local histories before they ever find……theres a great……Galaxy outside. don't……yourself know more about Helicon, right now, than……know about……rise of Trantor oooof……Great Interstellar War?"</p><p>铎丝说：“你目前读的都只是银河通史，应该查查某些小地方的特殊历史。在每个世界上，不论它多么小，学童也都要先学本星历史，然后才知晓外面还有个庞大的银河系。目前为止，你自己对赫利肯的了解，难道不比对川陀的兴起或‘星际大战’更多吗？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"That sort of knowledge is limited too," said Seldon gloomily. "I know Heliconian geography……the stories of……settlement……of……malfeasance……misfeasance of……planet Jennisek--thats……traditional enemy, though……teachers carefully told us that we ought to……traditional rival.……I never learned anything about……contributions of Helicon to general Galactic history."</p><p>“那种知识也有局限。”谢顿以沮丧的口吻说，“我知道赫利肯的地理、它的开拓史，以及詹尼瑟克这颗行星的恶行恶状……那个世界是我们的传统敌人，不过老师们曾经特别嘱咐，说我们应该称之为‘传统的对手’。可是，我从来没学到赫利肯对银河通史有什么贡献。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Maybe there werent any."</p><p>“或许根本没有。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Dont be silly. Of course there were. There……not have been great, huge space battles involving Helicon or crucial rebellions or peace treaties. There……not have been some Imperial competitor making……base on Helicon.……there must have been subtle influences. Surely, nothing……happen anywhere without affecting everywhere else.……theres nothing I……find to help……See here, Dors. In mathematics,……can be found in……computer; everything we know or have found……in twenty thousand years. In history, thats……so. Historians pick……choose……every……of them picks……chooses……same thing."</p><p>“别傻了，当然有。也许赫利肯未曾卷入任何大型的太空战事、重大的叛乱事件，或是重要的和平条约，也许没有哪个皇位竞逐者曾以赫利肯为基地，不过微妙的影响一定是存在的。不用说，任何一个角落发生的事件，都会对其他各个角落造成影响。但我找不到对我有任何帮助的资料……听我说，铎丝，在数学领域里，所有的一切都能在电脑中找到，包括过去两万年来我们所知道的或发现的一切。历史界则不然，历史学家总是挑挑拣拣，而且大家都挑拣相同的东西。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"But, Hari," said Dors, "mathematics is an ooderly thing of human invention.……thing follows from another. There……definitions……axioms,……of which……known. It is…… it is…………one piece. History is different. It is……unconscious working……of……deeds……thoughts of quadrillions of human beings. Historians must pick……choose."</p><p>“可是，哈里，”铎丝说，“数学是人类发明的秩序结构，一样东西紧扣着另一样。其中有定义，有公设，所有这些都是已知的。它是……它是……一个整体。历史则不同，它是万兆人口的行为和思想形成的无意识结构，历史学家必须挑挑拣拣。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Exactly," said Seldon, "but I must know……of history if I am to work……the laws of psychohistory."</p><p>“正是如此。”谢顿说，“但若想推出心理史学定律，我必须知晓全部的历史。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"In that case,……wont ever formulate……laws of psychohistory."</p><p>“那样的话，你将永远无法写下心理史学定律。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>That……yesterday.……Seldon……in……chair in……alcove, having spent another……of utter failure,……he could hear Dorss voice saying,……that case,……wont ever formulate……laws of psychohistory." </p><p>那是昨天的事。谢顿后来又花了一整天而毫无所获，这时正颓然坐在凹室中的椅子上。此刻，他还听得见铎丝的声音：“那样的话，你将永远无法写下心理史学定律。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>It……what he……thought to begin with……if it hadn't been……Hummins conviction to……contrary……his……ability to fire Seldon with……own blaze of conviction, Seldon would have continued to think……</p><p>这正是自己最初的想法。要不是夫铭坚决相信并非如此，若非他具有奇异的能力，将他的信念像火焰般喷到谢顿身上，谢顿会一直抱持同样的想法。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>And……neither could he quite……go. Might there……be some……out?</p><p>然而他却也无法真正放弃。难道就没有任何出路吗？</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He couldnt think of any.</p><p>他想不出任何解决之道。</p></div>

